Preliminary orders for new trailers fell to the lowest level in nearly a decade in June as fleets try to figure out their real needs after placing record orders in 2018.\cb1 \
\cb2 Net orders of 6,200 trailers were about half the total reported by ACT Research because cancellations swelled. Adjusting for seasonal factors brought volume to just over 7,000, said Frank Maly, ACT director of Commercial Vehicle Transportation Analysis and Research.\cb1 \
\cb2 \'93Despite indications earlier this year that fleets were anxious to place orders for 2020, discussions now indicate that fleets may have shifted to an extremely conservative stance,\'94 Maly said.\cb1 \
\cb2 Trailer makers that opened order books in June found few takers, said Don Ake, vice president of commercial vehicles at FTR Transportation Intelligence, which pegged net orders in June at 5,500. New trailer orders typically are placed in October.\cb1 \
\cb2 Both ACT\'92s and FTR\'92s reported preliminary orders in June were the lowest since September 2009.\cb1 \
